$ Registry: HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Office\{version}\{name}\Options

{ DeveloperTools #DeveloperTools

  If the value of `DeveloperTools` is set to `1`, the respective → Microsoft/Office application shows the *Developer* tab in the Ribbon:
  gh|about-Windows-Registry|/HKEY_CURRENT_USER/Software/Microsoft/Office/application_version/application_name/Options/img/DeveloperTools.png||


  The following → Windows/PowerShell script sets the value of `DeveloperTools` to 1 for a given Office Application:
  gh|about-Windows-Registry|/HKEY_CURRENT_USER/Software/Microsoft/Office/application_version/application_name/Options/DeveloperTools.ps1||

  In order to set the value for → Microsoft/Office/Word, the script can be invoked like so:
code {
.\DeveloperTools.ps1 Word
code }

}

sa:
  The corresponding → Windows/registry/tree-structure/key[registry keys] for
  → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_CURRENT_USER/Software/Microsoft/Office/application_version/Excel/Options[Excel] and
  → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_CURRENT_USER/Software/Microsoft/Office/application_version/Word/Options[Word].
